    <h1>About</h1>

    <p class="page-intro">
      
        I am Sabina Barcucci, and in my work life, I am a writer, consultant, former architect, and network tinkerer with longstanding ties to design. I’ve mostly worked in design hubs and through scientific research & innovation endowments - including in the cultural and museums world - as a project designer, innovator, communicator or community manager. I build multi-stakeholder projects that help; I support organisations with different scales and mandates to understand each other over complex ideas, regulations and cooperation projects; I am used to taking full responsibility in complex, multi-actor settings, where progress depends less on formal authority than on the ability to build trust, align expectations and keep different perspectives moving in the same direction. 
      </p>
     
    </section>

    <section class="page-section">
      <h2>Mastering EU funding to build a better world</h2>
      <p>
        I came to the conclusion that it’s impossible to build a better world in Europe without mastering our pooled funding mechanisms. So - after almost 13 years of career across engineering, design technology and cultural innovation - I spent the last 4 in Berlin becoming a technically sound go-to person for European cooperation initiatives, acting as an independent EU consultant across sectors and programs, and introducing The strategic access to EU funding* to a multiplicity of EU Funding “newcomer” organisations, from private multi-national academia to small civic society organisations. As my competence in this area had substantially grown over time, last December I could join as a senior consultant the grant office of an Italian R&I foundation whose business model is - since the late 90s - completely built around EU funded projects. This decision allowed me to take a break from my very energy-intensive newcomers and a full-project accountability, and to focus only on a very specific set of complementary horizontal support services for European R&I (Communication, Dissemination and Exploitation). While dramatically increasing the number and the complexity of the initiatives that I can lead, my experience at ICONS Innovation Strategies is helping me to fully acknowledge the tremendous level of competition for public funding across R&I sectors, as well as the needed level of coordination, optimisation and standardization in the EU arena that give organisations chances to achieve “the minimum viable excellence” to truly compete at EU level. Myself only, I lead the contribution to about 30 to 40 large Horizon consortia per year, hence at least 200 million € in funding requests pooled by at least 600 organisations. 
      </p>
    </section>

     <section class="page-section">
      <h2>Democracy Defence</h2>
      <p>
       In the three years prior to joining ICONS Foundation, I ran my own Berlin-based innovation consultancy Melville, and have been acting as an external leader of a very substantial body of projects mainly in the field of democracy innovation in partnership with Berlin and DACH region -based NGOs, such as the Public Libraries Empowering Active Democracy through media literacy, Empowering Citizens’ Assemblies in Germany and Austria for increasing policy uptake and systemic change in Democracy, engagements labs and Democratic Leadership programs for Young Women, strategy for DEVELOPING A STRATEGIC TRANSNATIONAL  PARTNERSHIP FOR DEMOCRATIC RESILIENCE, an extensive capacity building regranting program lasting Four-Years Funding and Capacity Building programme to boost European Democracy Immune System by supporting German Grassroots Activists against Racism and Right Wing Extremism (CERV), the development of preparatory ecosystem work for the deployment of a DEI Data Space - Data ecosystem for diversity, equity and inclusion in Germany (BMFB), the Circular Social Trust: Composite KPIs for e-waste to infer social wellbeing of pickers in west Africa, the P+ARTS - Partnership for Research in Technology and Sustainability (Next Generation EU), a project that - by raising 7.2M EUR - developed a nationwide PhD program across 10 Italian higher education institutions, and supported the development of a more connected and meaningful creative and artistic sector to participate in burning topics in business, policy, cultural and research sectors. Previously and during that time, I spent one year as a core member of the event-running team that produced the Berlin-based popular conferences of Disruption Network Lab, a cultural outlet connecting OSINT communities, investigative journalists and big tech whistleblowers. I led the community and conference program, by managing whistleblowers such as Julian Hessenthaler, who triggered corruption investigations that ended the political career of former Austrian chancellor Sebastian Kurz; Anas Aremeyaw Anas, a Ghanaian undercover investigative journalist; Frederik Obermaier, initiator of Panama Papers. In 2023 I also curated community events on eerie topics infamously populating the AI doomerism cultural mainstream debate in 2026: a mad mix of religious ethos, elitism and techno-autoritarianism, that connects existential risks, eschatology and techno-billionaires. 
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section">
      <h2>Community-based cultural innovation</h2>
      <p>
       Across 2018 and the COVID19 years, thanks to two large grants from the Italian Foundation Compagnia di San Paolo, I explored the cultural innovation management work on streaming technologies for two very different cultural institutions: the brand new music & community based young cultural center in Turin “Imbarchino del Valentino”, and the 20-years-old established, at that time “dusty” and institutionalised “Science Festival of Genoa”.
innovating the oldest and largest Italian science festival, the outreach of the National Research Council, a nationwide institution built during fascism to ensure scientific and industrial autarchy, and still the largest Italian public research institution. My mission was to digitally transition formats and operations, and to innovate the organisation’s mission, to trespass the institutional stiffness and somehow obsolescence in which the festival had fallen. In an historical moment where no institution could anymore be the gatekeeper of “good science” against global conspiracy theories surfing through social media user generated scientific fake-news, the chosen approach was indeed to strengthen connection of the institution with its large community assets (thousands of science communicators and associations). We designed a more meaningful scientific outreach structure involving training programs on how to become a “science streamer”, or on public engagement in science (how to train researchers to involve their stakeholders and public in the research process), while over almost 3 years, I introduced agile methods for internal production, authored a few innovative pilots, and then released a policy brief analysis on “why and how the festival should become an impact-driven organisation by activating a research-public ecosystem through community engagement”, and drafted a funding strategy for this idea. 

    </section>

